HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1542
By McCalmon
A RESOLUTION to honor Page High School on the occasion of its
fiftieth anniversary.
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should recognize
those exemplary educational institutions that have made significant contributions, through an
abiding commitment to excellence, to their respective communities and to this State; and
WHEREAS, one such noteworthy institution is Page High School in Williamson County,
which celebrated the fiftieth anniversary of its founding in 2025; and
WHEREAS, Page High School is an important educational institution whose history
reflects both the growth of the region and broader changes in public education; since its
founding in the mid-1970s, the school has evolved from a small, rural campus into a modern
high school serving a rapidly expanding suburban population; and
WHEREAS, named in honor of Fred J. Page, a highly influential superintendent, the
school opened its doors in 1975 in the rural community of Rudderville, just outside Franklin; the
school was built on approximately forty acres of farmland at a cost of nearly $3 million; and
WHEREAS, in its early decades, Page served farming communities, and the school
reflected the rural lifestyle of the region; this connection was reinforced through agricultural
education programs, which continue today through career and technical education pathways in
agribusiness and veterinary sciences, as well as a highly active FFA; and
WHEREAS, as the surrounding area experienced rapid development, the school
underwent multiple renovations and expansions beginning in the 1980s; despite its growth,
Page High School has maintained close ties to its rural roots, fostering a strong sense of
community and tradition that distinguish it from more urban schools; and
HJR1542
018198
